Substituting these into the expression, we get

$$
\frac{(3^5)^n \times 3^{2n + 1}}{(3^2)^n \times 3^{n - 1}}
$$

Using the power rule $(a^m)^n = a^{mn}$, we rewrite the expression as

$$
\frac{3^{5n} \times 3^{2n + 1}}{3^{2n} \times 3^{n - 1}}
$$

Using the product rule $a^m \times a^n = a^{m+n}$, we combine the exponents in the numerator and denominator:

$$
\frac{3^{5n + 2n + 1}}{3^{2n + n - 1}}
=
\frac{3^{7n + 1}}{3^{3n - 1}}
$$

Using the quotient rule $\frac{a^m}{a^n} = a^{m-n}$, we subtract the exponents:

$$
3^{(7n + 1) - (3n - 1)}
=
3^{7n + 1 - 3n + 1}
=
3^{4n + 2}
$$

